If you really need to search for the nearest lower temperature in the range `[i - 1, i + 1]` (between &#39;neighbour&#39; days, closest indices), where `i` is the current day index:

**Using a HashMap**:
```
private int getLowerTemperature(Map&lt;Integer, Integer&gt; temperatures, int searchDay) {
        int dayIndex = searchDay - 1;

        int previousDayTemp = temperatures.getOrDefault(dayIndex - 1, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        int currentDayTemp = temperatures.getOrDefault(dayIndex, Integer.MAX_VALUE);
        int nextDayTemp = temperatures.getOrDefault(dayIndex + 1, Integer.MAX_VALUE);

        return Math.min(previousDayTemp, Math.min(currentDayTemp, nextDayTemp));
    }
```
***Complexities***:
O(1) - space,
O(1) - time


**Using an ArrayList**:
```
    private int getLowerTemperature(List&lt;Integer&gt; temperatures, int searchDay) {
        int dayIndex = searchDay - 1;
        if (temperatures.size() &lt; 2 || dayIndex &gt; temperatures.size()) {
            return temperatures.get(0);
        }

        int currentDayTemp = temperatures.get(dayIndex);
        // corner cases
        if (dayIndex == 0) {
            return Math.min(currentDayTemp, temperatures.get(dayIndex + 1));
        }
        if (dayIndex == temperatures.size() - 1) {
            return Math.min(temperatures.get(dayIndex - 1), currentDayTemp);
        }

        int previousDayTemp = temperatures.get(dayIndex - 1);
        int nextDayTemp = temperatures.get(dayIndex + 1);

        return Math.min(previousDayTemp, Math.min(currentDayTemp, nextDayTemp));
    }
```
Actually here you don&#39;t need `List&lt;Integer&gt; days` if every index of `List&lt;Integer&gt; temperatures` corresponds to its day. 

***Complexities***:
O(1) - space,
O(1) - time

